---
// Colophon: how the site is made and why. The page doubles as a specimen —
// the palette row and type scale below are built from the same tokens they
// describe, so they stay correct in both themes by construction.
import { SITE } from '../config/site';
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const palette = [
  { token: '--paper', cls: 'bg-paper', role: 'ground' },
  { token: '--paper-raised', cls: 'bg-paper-raised', role: 'panels' },
  { token: '--stone', cls: 'bg-stone', role: 'shadows' },
  { token: '--ink', cls: 'bg-ink', role: 'text' },
  { token: '--ember', cls: 'bg-ember', role: 'accent' },
];

const scale = [
  { token: '--step-4', size: '2.441rem', cls: 'text-step-4' },
  { token: '--step-3', size: '1.953rem', cls: 'text-step-3' },
  { token: '--step-2', size: '1.563rem', cls: 'text-step-2' },
  { token: '--step-1', size: '1.25rem', cls: 'text-step-1' },
  { token: '--step-0', size: '1rem', cls: 'text-step-0' },
  { token: '--step--1', size: '0.8rem', cls: 'text-step--1' },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title={`Colophon — ${SITE.name}`}
  description="How this site is made: the design thinking, the type, the palette and the stack behind it."
>
  <article class="py-16">
    <header class="max-w-[var(--measure-prose)]">
      <p class="tracking-label text-step--1 uppercase" aria-hidden="true">// colophon</p>
      <h1 class="text-step-4 mt-4 font-bold">About this site</h1>
      <p class="text-step-1 mt-6">
        This site is its own case study. Here is how it is made, and why it looks the way it
        does.
      </p>
    </header>

    <hr class="my-14" />

    <section aria-labelledby="design-heading" class="max-w-[var(--measure-prose)]">
      <h2 id="design-heading" class="text-step-2 font-bold">The design</h2>
      <p class="mt-6">
        I think of the style as a field terminal: graph-paper warmth with terminal precision, a
        well-kept engineer's notebook rendered by a machine. It has to read as deliberate to a
        churchwarden and competent to a developer with the source open, so every choice leans
        towards restraint.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4">
        The palette is six values, each with one job. Paper is the ground, printed with a fine
        grid. Ink carries all text and borders. Stone does the quiet work of shadows and
        hairlines. Ember is the only accent, and it is rationed to one highlight per view.
        Colour here is a role, not decoration.
      </p>

      <figure class="mt-8">
        <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-4">
          {
            palette.map(({ token, cls, role }) => (
              <div class="flex w-28 flex-col gap-2">
                <div class:list={['h-16 w-16 border border-ink', cls]} />
                <p class="text-step--1">
                  {token}
                  <br />
                  <span class="tracking-label uppercase">{role}</span>
                </p>
              </div>
            ))
          }
        </div>
        <figcaption class="text-step--1 mt-4">
          The swatches are live tokens, not images. Flip the theme in the header and watch them
          trade places: ink becomes the ground, paper becomes the text, and the grid stays.
        </figcaption>
      </figure>

      <p class="mt-8">
        Depth is literal. Panels are raised paper with a hard offset shadow, no blur, because
        nothing on this site floats. Corners are square everywhere; that is policy, not
        oversight. Sections are separated by rules and whitespace rather than cards, since in a
        layout this plain, space is the luxury signal.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4">
        The dark theme is not a second palette. Six custom properties swap and every component
        follows; none of them knows which theme it is in.
      </p>
    </section>

    <hr class="my-14" />

    <section aria-labelledby="type-heading" class="max-w-[var(--measure-prose)]">
      <h2 id="type-heading" class="text-step-2 font-bold">The type</h2>
      <p class="mt-6">
        Everything is set in Commit Mono, self-hosted as subset woff2 files so nothing is
        fetched from a third party. One face for headings, body and labels sounds like a
        limitation; in practice the discipline is the identity. A monospace face keeps
        alignment honest and gives the page its measured voice.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4">
        Sizes come from a strict modular scale, ratio 1.25 on a 1rem base. There are no
        arbitrary values anywhere; every size on this page is one of these:
      </p>

      <figure class="bg-paper-raised shadow-raised mt-8 border border-ink p-6">
        <dl class="space-y-5">
          {
            scale.map(({ token, size, cls }) => (
              <div>
                {/* Lowercase on purpose: the labels quote real token names. */}
                <dt class="text-step--1 tracking-label">
                  {token} &middot; {size}
                </dt>
                <dd class:list={['mt-1', cls]}>Paper, ink, stone, ember</dd>
              </div>
            ))
          }
        </dl>
      </figure>

      <p class="mt-8">
        Letter-spacing is tokenised too: 0.03rem for body text, 0.1rem for navigation and
        labels, and a wide 0.5rem held in reserve for rare display moments. No faux weights;
        the regular, bold and italic cuts are the only ones shipped.
      </p>
    </section>

    <hr class="my-14" />

    <section aria-labelledby="cube-heading" class="max-w-[var(--measure-prose)]">
      <h2 id="cube-heading" class="text-step-2 font-bold">
        The cube <span class="tracking-label text-step--1 align-middle uppercase" aria-hidden="true">[wip]</span>
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-6">
        The hero holds a reserved square, and the reservation is deliberate. It belongs to the
        site's one signature interaction: a WebGL cube, each face textured with real project
        work and tinted to the palette so photography cannot break the world. It will idle
        slowly, spin under drag, stop idling entirely when you ask for reduced motion, and fall
        back to a static image without JavaScript.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4">
        It ships as the only script island on the site, initialised lazily after first paint.
        Everything else stays still so that one thing can move. It is on the workbench now;
        until it lands, the hero says so.
      </p>
    </section>

    <hr class="my-14" />

    <section aria-labelledby="stack-heading" class="max-w-[var(--measure-prose)]">
      <h2 id="stack-heading" class="text-step-2 font-bold">The stack</h2>
      <p class="mt-6">
        The tools are chosen for the same reason as the whitespace: to stay out of the way.
      </p>

      <dl class="mt-8">
        {
          [
            ['framework', 'Astro, static output. Every page is HTML before it is anything else.'],
            [
              'styling',
              'Tailwind CSS v4, CSS-first. The tokens live as custom properties and map straight into the theme.',
            ],
            ['type', 'Commit Mono, subset woff2, font-display swap.'],
            [
              'hosting',
              'Cloudflare Pages, deployed from GitHub on push. The contact form runs as a Pages Function.',
            ],
            [
              'scripts',
              'A few lines of vanilla JS for the theme toggle and the contact form. The cube will be the only island.',
            ],
            ['budget', 'Under 300KB on first load, fonts and cube included.'],
          ].map(([term, detail]) => (
            <div class="border-stone flex flex-col gap-1 border-t py-4 sm:flex-row sm:gap-6">
              <dt class="tracking-label text-step--1 uppercase sm:w-32 sm:shrink-0 sm:pt-1">
                {term}
              </dt>
              <dd>{detail}</dd>
            </div>
          ))
        }
      </dl>

      <p class="mt-8">
        If you would like to check any of this, view source. That is partly who I built it
        for.
      </p>
    </section>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
